K Means Clustering - Wine Data Set

Problem Statement:

Cluster the given dataset into segments. The dataset has parameters indicating the metrics of wine samples.

Usually when dealing with an unsupervised learning problem, its difficult to get a good measure of how well the model performed. So we shall take a dataset for which we know the output and test the model performance.

Step 1: Import Data

df1<-read.csv('C:\\Users\\Windows\\Desktop\\data sci\\k means algorithm 25.11\\R\\winequality-red.csv',sep=";")
df2<-read.csv('C:\\Users\\Windows\\Desktop\\data sci\\k means algorithm 25.11\\R\\winequality-white.csv',sep=";")

Now add a label column to both df1 and df2 indicating a label ‘red’ or ‘white’. - Output column mentioning the group name.

Step 2: Exploratory Data Analysis

1: Create a Histogram of residual sugar from the wine data. Color by red and white wines.

library(ggplot2)

pl <- ggplot(wine,aes(x=residual.sugar))+geom_histogram(aes(fill=label),color='black',bins=100)
pl + scale_fill_manual(values = c('#ae4554','#faf7ea')) + theme_bw()

pl

Create a scatterplot of volatile.acidity versus residual.sugar, color by red and white wine.

pl<-ggplot(wine,aes(x=volatile.acidity,y=residual.sugar))+geom_point(aes(color=label),alpha=0.4)
pl

pl <- ggplot(wine,aes(x=volatile.acidity,y=residual.sugar)) + geom_point(aes(color=label),alpha=0.2)
# Optional adding of fill colors
pl + scale_color_manual(values = c('#ae4554','#faf7ea')) +theme_dark()

## Step 3: KMeans ML Model for Bulding the Clusters

wine.cl <- kmeans(wine[1:12],2)
print(wine.cl$centers)

Step 4: Evaluating the Clusters

table(wine$label,wine.cl$cluster)
##        
##            1    2
##   red     85 1514
##   white 3604 1294

Thus, there are 1310 samples from white wine category grouped as red wine by the model. These samples will be reconsidered for inspection by the Quality check team. Accuracy % : 80% ((1515+3588)/6)
